SASAC Pool usage

This notebook analyses and visualises how many slots are booked at St Albans' Sub Aqua Club. Since the pool is not heated, it is obviously a lot more popular in the summer months. But by how much?

This report is based on the bookings made on skedda. Bookings can be made for 15-minute intervals. We consider each 15 minutes interval a slot. If the splash zone is not in use, there are 32 slots every 15 minutes, so 128 slots per hour. So if a particular slot has a 25% occupancy, that means there should be 8 people in the pool.

Summary

In 2024, overall average occupancy is lower in June (8%), July (9%) & August (11%) than in May (10%) and September (13%). Even at popular times (defined as the upper quartile of slots, the 25% most popular slots), pool occupancy is very low in the winter months (6%, or 2 people in the pool during these slots) and low during summer months (12%, 4 people). September 2024 has been the busiest month, with popular slots reaching 19% occupancy.

The usage pattern changes in the summer months compared to the rest of the year. Morning pool usage (before 1pm) is lower in the summer than in May and September, dropping below 10%, but afternoon usage is substantially higher (on average around 20%). During heat waves, pool occupancy is higher, with average occupancy reaching 70% for those days. Splash pool usage is even more pronounced, with the splash area almost exclusively being used during heat waves and good weather.

Occupancy has only annecdotally been compared to water temperature. The overall trend in water temperature correlates with occupancy, but on a daily level, water temperatures only change slightly while occupancy changes dramatically. In the summer, before 3pm the pool seems to be particularly under-utilised considering the warm water temperatures.

Data gathering

The month view in skedda is populated through a JSON object that contains all bookings over two months. For example, the previous link opens the monthly booking view for June 2024. The browser populates this by fetching https://sasac.skedda.com/bookingslists?end=2024-08-14T23:59:59.999&start=2024-05-27T00:00:00, i.e. all bookings from 27 May to 14 August. We can simply save this JSON file using Firefox/Chrome's Developer Tools, and parse it here. Since we can extract 2 months at a time, extracting a years worth of data requires 6 page loads and maybe 30 clicks in total.

The JSON object contains personal identifying information for the logged in user (i.e. myself), but not for anyone else. The raw data is not included in this repo, but a combined CSV with all the relevant information (start time, end time, lanes) of the bookings is.

Lane information

Skedda includes all metadata (lane names, opening hours, user types) in the json retrieved from https://sasac.skedda.com/webs (again via devtools). The only useful information here is the lane names, and they don't seem to have changed ever, but it might be still worth checking from time to time, that spaces < 671206 are Lane Slots and spaces >= 671206 remain Splash Slots.

Sunrise, sunset, opening hours

This information is not historically available through skedda, so we calculate this as required.

Splash zone opening hours

Normally there are 32 slots available for booking. When the splash zone is available, there are 15 normal lanes available and 20 splash zones slots available, for a total of 35 slots. Ideally we would have historic information on splash zone opening hours, but for now we just treat them all as normal lanes, but weigh them at 1 splash zone slot = 17/20 normal slots.

Reproducible analysis

The html version of this report does not show any of the code, but it is possible to view all code that parses the json and analysis the data in the accompanying .ipynb notebook.

Data range

The data analysed in this notebook spans 1557 days, from 01/04/2021 to 06/07/2025. In total, there were 53258 bookings.

Utilisation plots

Considering each day as a datapoint, the following figure shows the pool utilisation per day.

Granted, that is not a very useful figure for understanding what is going on, but it looks pretty.

Box and Whisker plots by Month/Week

The following figures plot box and whisker plots of the pool utilisation for various months and weeks. The line splitting the box in two represents the median value. This shows that 50% of the data lies on the left hand side of the median value and 50% lies on the right hand side. The left edge of the box represents the lower quartile; it shows the value at which the first 25% of the data falls up to. The right edge of the box shows the upper quartile; it shows that 25% of the data lies to the right of the upper quartile value. The values at which the horizontal lines stop at are the values of the upper and lower values of the data excluding any outliers (1.5*Interquartile range (IQR)). The single points on the diagram show the outliers.

Some observations on this:

  • During the winter months utilisation is very low.
  • In the summer months the 75% utilisation rate increases to above 30%, but the median barely exceeds 10%.
  • There are lots of outliers: days when the pool is very busy.

Detailed comparison May 2025 vs June 2025

<pandas.core.groupby.generic.DataFrameGroupBy object at 0x0000025E862E9250>

Some observations:

  • 31st of May was a lot busier than 1st June, despite the weather being similar: Clearly winter-only members had a last go.
  • 13th, 19-22 and 28-30 June correspond to heat-wave days. While this only has a minor influence on the pool temperature (the water takes time to heat up), it means the pool is a lot busier. There is strong drop-off after the end of the heat-wave.
  • This heatwave-based picture is also visible in May, but weaker, and the drop-off afterwards is less pronounced.

Findings:

  • mean usage is higher or the same before midday in May than in June (e.g. mean of 12% on hours 10am, 11am, and 12am (so 10am-1pm) in May, compared to a mean of 11%, 11%, and 12% for the same hours in June). 8-9am is an exception.
  • Afternoons are substantially busier in June than in May, with mean usage peaking at 23% at 5-6pm in June, compared to 12% in May.
